            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wherefore they cried so against him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rev. Ver.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " has “for what cause they so shouted against him,” and the verb is rendered “gave a shout” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 12:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but there it is the voice of the applauding crowd that is spoken of. In this verse and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the only other passage in which the word is found in N. T.) “cry” seems to express better in English the utterance of an infuriated mob. It is true that a different verb is rendered by “cry” in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 22:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but that proves that the Greeks had two verbs which they could use for the noise of a mob, while in English we appear not to be so rich. In the A. V. “shout” seems always used of triumph and exultation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
